-- South African Stocks: Anglo, BHP, AngloGold, Harmony, Massmart
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2011-12-23T07:59:35Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-23/south-african-stocks-anglo-bhp-anglogold-harmony-massmart.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index 
advanced for a second day, rising 0.6 percent to 32,089.05 by
9:20 a.m. in Johannesburg, headed for its highest close in more
than a week. The index has gained less than 0.1 percent this
year.  The following are among the most active equities in the
South African market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the mining company that makes
up about 9 percent of the benchmark  stock index , increased for a
second day, adding 0.7 percent to 302 rand. Copper rose for a
fourth day in  London  on speculation signs of growth in the  U.S.
economy  will support demand for industrial metals.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest miner,
increased 1.1 percent to 242.50 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , South Africa’s biggest
gold producer, snapped a two-day losing streak, rising 0.7
percent to 349 rand. Gold climbed and was set for the first
weekly gain in three after better-than-expected U.S. economic
data damped demand for the dollar as a haven investment.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , one of South Africa’s largest
producers of the metal, added 1.4 percent to 128.50 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR)  , Africa’s third-biggest
gold producer, advanced 1.8 percent to 99.72 rand.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  , a retailer controlled by
Wal-Mart Stores Inc., climbed 1.4 percent to 173.34 rand, headed
for its highest close since its shares started trading on the
Johannesburg bourse. South Africa’s Competition Tribunal
conditionally approved acquisitions made by the company of The
Fruit Spot and stores owned by The Rhino Group.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
